[2
Date: Wed, 31 Oct 2001 09:16:53 -0800 (PST)
From: <"slminnick@ucdavis.edu>
Source: San Francisco Chronicle 31 Oct 2001 [edited

Fifteen people who came in contact with cows that died of anthrax in
Santa Clara County have been treated with antibiotics as a
precautionary measure, the California Department of Food and
Agriculture said yesterday. Twenty beef cattle died at a ranch 5 miles
south of Morgan Hill between 20-26 Oct 2001.
The disease was misdiagnosed by a private veterinarian first summoned
to the ranch, and he performed 2 necropsies at the scene -- an
ill-advised practice when dealing with anthrax, because it brings
people into direct contact with diseased tissue, experts say.
The veterinarian, 2 owners of the livestock, 2 ranch hands and 10
workers at the laboratory to which samples of the dead animals' tissue
were sent were all treated with the antibiotic Cipro as a
precautionary measure. The lab workers were treated by campus
physicians at the University of California at Davis. None has shown
any symptoms of anthrax.
The incident "does not pose a threat to the general public," said
Santa Clara County health officer Dr. Martin Fenstersheib. "The only
people at risk are those coming into direct contact with the blood,
tissue or other body fluids of infected animals." The remaining 120
cattle in the herd have been vaccinated against anthrax and
quarantined for 60 days.
Anthrax spores, which can lie dormant in the soil for half a century
or more, are widespread in California's rangeland. The pastures where
the afflicted cattle were grazing were dry, and the grass was sparse.
Animals that "graze closer to the ground . . . may be more likely to
ingest spores," the Department of Food and Agriculture said in a
statement.
Before these deaths, California had just 10 reported cases in the past
decade. In 1991, anthrax killed 28 cattle in Contra Costa County. In
1984, 43 cattle and 135 sheep died of anthrax in San Luis Obispo
County.
[Byline: Eric Brazil, Chronicle Staff Writer
--
Sharon Minnick
UC Davis Epidemiology, California
